{{DISPLAYTITLE:''N''-topological space}}

{{orphan|date=June 2013}}

In [[mathematics]], an '''''N''-topological space''' is a set equipped with ''N'' arbitrary topologies. If ''œÑ''<sub>1</sub>,&nbsp;''œÑ''<sub>2</sub>,&nbsp;...,&nbsp;''œÑ''<sub>''N''</sub> are ''N''&nbsp;topologies defined on a nonempty set '''X''', then the ''N''-topological space is denoted by (''X'',''œÑ''<sub>1</sub>,''œÑ''<sub>2</sub>,...,''œÑ''<sub>''N''</sub>).
For ''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;1, the structure is simply a [[topological space]].
For ''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;2, the structure becomes a [[bitopological space]] introduced by J. C. Kelly.<ref name="J. C. Kelly">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=J. C.|title=Bitopological spaces|journal=Proc. London Math. Soc.|year=1963|volume=13|issue=3|pages=71‚Äì89|doi=10.1112/plms/s3-13.1.71}}</ref>

== Example ==
Let ''X''&nbsp;=&nbsp;{''x''<sub>1</sub>, ''x''<sub>2</sub>, ...., ''x''<sub>''n''</sub>} be any finite set. Suppose ''A''<sub>''r''</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;{''x''<sub>1</sub>, ''x''<sub>2</sub>, ..., ''x''<sub>''r''</sub>}. Then the collection ''œÑ''<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;{''œÜ'',&nbsp;''A''<sub>1</sub>, ''A''<sub>2</sub>, ..., ''A''<sub>''n''</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;''X''} will be a topology on&nbsp;''X''. If ''œÑ''<sub>1</sub>, ''œÑ''<sub>2</sub>, ..., ''œÑ''<sub>''m''</sub> be ''m'' such topologies (chain topologies) defined on ''X'', then the structure (''X'', ''œÑ''<sub>1</sub>, ''œÑ''<sub>2</sub>, ..., ''œÑ''<sub>''m''</sub>) is an '''''m''-topological space'''.

