'''Person of Jewish ethnicity''' ({{lang-ru|'''–õ–∏—Ü–æ –µ–≤—Ä–µ–π—Å–∫–æ–π –Ω–∞—Ü–∏–æ–Ω–∞–ª—å–Ω–æ—Å—Ç–∏'''}}) is –∞ Russian [[euphemism]] that was invented as a [[politically correct]] alternative term for an [[ethnic Jew]]. It was invented because [[Jew (word)|the word "Jew"]] became [[derogatory]] during [[Antisemitism in the Soviet Union|Soviet antisemitic campaigns]].<ref name="Sarnov">[[Benedikt Sarnov]],''Our Soviet Newspeak: A Short Encyclopedia of Real Socialism.'', Moscow: 2002, {{ISBN|5-85646-059-6}} (–ù–∞—à —Å–æ–≤–µ—Ç—Å–∫–∏–π –Ω–æ–≤–æ—è–∑. –ú–∞–ª–µ–Ω—å–∫–∞—è —ç–Ω—Ü–∏–∫–ª–æ–ø–µ–¥–∏—è —Ä–µ–∞–ª—å–Ω–æ–≥–æ —Å–æ—Ü–∏–∞–ª–∏–∑–º–∞.), "Persons of Jewish ethnicity", pages 287-293.</ref><ref name="RFERL">[http://www.svobodanews.ru/content/article/411203.html Person of Jewish ethnicity], [[RFE/RL]]</ref>
Several officially sanctioned antisemitic campaigns took place in the Soviet Union, most notably the [[Doctor's Plot]] and the struggle against the "[[rootless cosmopolitans]]". However, the entire Jewish population was never openly and officially declared the [[enemy of the people]].<ref name="Sarnov"/> Instead, several [[euphemism]]s were used, such as [[zionists]], [[rootless cosmopolitans]] and "persons of Jewish ethnicity". There was an important distinction between these words: ''zionist'' and ''rootless cosmopolitans'' served as a label for "bad Jews" as enemies of the state, whereas "persons of Jewish ethnicity" was a [[politically correct]] expression for good, loyal Jews who were called by some ordinary folks as ''trained'' Jews (the original Russian word "–¥—Ä–µ—Å–∏—Ä–æ–≤–∞–Ω–Ω—ã–µ" (dressage) typically refers to animals trained to perform in circus).<ref name="Sarnov"/> However most people realized that all these euphemisms denoted ''all'' Jews. A dean of [[Marxism-Leninism]] department at one of Soviet Universities explained the policy to his students:<ref name="Sarnov"/>
{{Quotation|1=One of you asked if our current political campaign can be regarded as [[antisemitism|antisemitic]]. Comrade [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] said: "We hate Nazi not because they are Germans, but because they brought enormous suffering to our land". Same can be said about the Jews.}}
The analogous euphemism "person of Caucasian ethnicity" is used less frequently in modern Russian to refer to [[Racism in Russia#Peoples of the Caucasus|peoples of the Caucasus]], such as [[Georgians in Russia|Georgians]] or [[Armenians in Russia]].<ref name="Sarnov"/><ref name="RFERL"/>
